Substitute \(x = y + 2\) into the first equation:
\begin{align*}
3(y + 2) + 2y &= 10 \\
3y + 6 + 2y &= 10 \\
5y + 6 &= 10 \\
5y &= 4 \\
y &= \frac{4}{5}
\end{align*}

Substitute \(y = \frac{4}{5}\) back into \(x = y + 2\):
\begin{align*}
x &= \frac{4}{5} + 2 \\
x &= \frac{4}{5} + \frac{10}{5} \\
x &= \frac{14}{5}
\end{align*}

